01:17:56,450 --> 01:17:58,450
What happens?

1611
01:17:58,450 --> 01:18:02,450
The magnetic charge becomes more, the magnetic charges start

1612
01:18:02,450 --> 01:18:06,450
to play the role that the electric charges originally did.

1613
01:18:06,450 --> 01:18:10,450
The electric charges become the complicated heavy things.

1614
01:18:10,450 --> 01:18:14,450
The magnetic charges become the simple light things.

1615
01:18:14,450 --> 01:18:19,950
The question of whether something is composite or fundamental

1616
01:18:19,950 --> 01:18:25,450
is, should really be asked in the following way.

1617
01:18:26,450 --> 01:18:28,950
You should ask, is it useful to

1618
01:18:28,950 --> 01:18:31,450
think of it one way or the other?

1619
01:18:31,450 --> 01:18:34,950
And whether it's useful or not may depend

1620
01:18:34,950 --> 01:18:38,450
on the values of the parameters in the theory.

1621
01:18:38,450 --> 01:18:39,450
It may depend on the values.

1622
01:18:39,450 --> 01:18:42,450
They may depend on the environment.

1623
01:18:42,450 --> 01:18:45,450
There might even be situations where there

1624
01:18:45,450 --> 01:18:48,450
are control knobs that you can turn,

1625
01:18:48,450 --> 01:18:51,450
which winds up turning the magnetic charges

1626
01:18:51,450 --> 01:18:54,450
into something more fundamental than the electric charges.

1627
01:18:54,450 --> 01:18:55,450
This really can happen.

1628
01:18:55,450 --> 01:18:57,450
You can imagine this happening.

1629
01:18:57,450 --> 01:19:03,450
And so there's no invariant ultimate answer to the question,

1630
01:19:03,450 --> 01:19:05,450
which is more fundamental, the

1631
01:19:05,450 --> 01:19:07,450
magnetic charge or the electric charge?

1632
01:19:07,450 --> 01:19:09,450
It's a question of which is useful.

1633
01:19:09,450 --> 01:19:13,450
I remember this question came up

1634
01:19:13,450 --> 01:19:17,450
in a Solvay conference once in Texas.

1635
01:19:17,450 --> 01:19:20,450
Oh, it must have been 20, 25 years ago.

1636
01:19:20,450 --> 01:19:21,450
I don't remember.

1637
01:19:21,450 --> 01:19:22,450
And I was giving a lecture.

1638
01:19:22,450 --> 01:19:24,450
The lecture was on the Higgs boson.

1639
01:19:24,450 --> 01:19:27,950
And the question was, is the

1640
01:19:27,950 --> 01:19:31,450
Higgs boson fundamental or is it composite?

1641
01:19:31,450 --> 01:19:34,450
And I was describing a theory

1642
01:19:34,450 --> 01:19:37,450
in which the Higgs boson is composite.

1643
01:19:37,450 --> 01:19:39,450
And Eugene Wigner, the famous

1644
01:19:39,450 --> 01:19:41,450
Eugene Wigner, who raises his hand,

1645
01:19:41,450 --> 01:19:44,450
and he said, was means composite.

1646
01:19:44,450 --> 01:19:46,950
And I said, that means, you know, things

1647
01:19:46,950 --> 01:19:49,450
made out of little pieces and so forth.

1648
01:19:49,450 --> 01:19:52,450
Yeah, but was means composite.

1649
01:19:52,450 --> 01:19:53,450
And I explained it over and over again.

1650
01:19:53,450 --> 01:19:58,450
And he said, no, it doesn't mean composite.

1651
01:19:58,450 --> 01:20:02,450
What composite means is that it can't be broken up.

1652
01:20:02,450 --> 01:20:04,450
It can't decay.

1653
01:20:04,450 --> 01:20:05,450
It can't decay.

1654
01:20:05,450 --> 01:20:06,450
A thing can't decay.

1655
01:20:06,450 --> 01:20:07,450
No, sorry.

1656
01:20:07,450 --> 01:20:09,450
Fundamental means it can't decay.

1657
01:20:09,450 --> 01:20:11,450
And composite means it can decay.

1658
01:20:11,450 --> 01:20:12,450
It can break up.

1659
01:20:12,450 --> 01:20:14,450
It can fall apart.

1660
01:20:14,450 --> 01:20:16,450
So I asked him, well, Eugene, do you think

1661
01:20:16,450 --> 01:20:18,450
that that means that the hydrogen atom is fundamental

1662
01:20:18,450 --> 01:20:20,450
because the ground state of the hydrogen

1663
01:20:20,450 --> 01:20:22,450
atom is fundamental because it can't decay?

1664
01:20:22,450 --> 01:20:27,450
No, no, no, no, no.

1665
01:20:27,450 --> 01:20:29,450
And we started to talk about the proton.

1666
01:20:29,450 --> 01:20:31,450
The proton can't decay.

1667
01:20:31,450 --> 01:20:33,450
Is it fundamental?

1668
01:20:33,450 --> 01:20:36,450
And the neutron not fundamental because it can decay.

1669
01:20:36,450 --> 01:20:39,450
And the whole argument got really crazy.

1670
01:20:39,450 --> 01:20:42,450
Nobody was making any progress in explaining what,

1671
01:20:42,450 --> 01:20:45,450
and everybody and his brother had some

1672
01:20:45,450 --> 01:20:48,450
opinion about what composite and fundamental means.

1673
01:20:48,450 --> 01:20:51,450
And finally, Gerard, at Hooft,

1674
01:20:51,450 --> 01:20:54,450
who was always the most sensible person at these things,

1675
01:20:54,450 --> 01:20:56,450
got up and simply said,

1676
01:20:56,450 --> 01:20:58,950
a thing is fundamental when it's

1677
01:20:58,950 --> 01:21:01,450
useful to think of it as fundamental.

1678
01:21:01,450 --> 01:21:03,450
And everybody shut up because

1679
01:21:03,450 --> 01:21:05,450
they knew he was absolutely right.

1680
01:21:08,450 --> 01:21:12,450
That is, now, are strings fundamental?

1681
01:21:12,450 --> 01:21:15,450
There is one set of parameters in the theory where

1682
01:21:15,450 --> 01:21:18,450
strings are made up out of little things called D-brains.

1683
01:21:18,450 --> 01:21:21,450
You change the parameters and you find a D-brain.

1684
01:21:21,450 --> 01:21:24,450
D-brains are made up out of the strings.

1685
01:21:24,450 --> 01:21:29,450
So it's a question of useful.

1686
01:21:29,450 --> 01:21:32,950
There are ranges of the parameters of the theory where it

1687
01:21:32,950 --> 01:21:36,450
is useful to think of the strings as the most fundamental objects.

1688
01:21:36,450 --> 01:21:39,450
You can shift the parameters and find ranges

1689
01:21:39,450 --> 01:21:42,450
of parameters where the things that are called D-brains,

1690
01:21:42,450 --> 01:21:45,450
which previously had been thought of as

1691
01:21:45,450 --> 01:21:48,450
big fat composite objects similar to the monopoles,

1692
01:21:48,450 --> 01:21:50,450
morph into tiny things,

1693
01:21:50,450 --> 01:21:54,450
and the strings themselves blow up into big fat composites.

1694
01:21:54,450 --> 01:21:57,950
This is a lesson that I think

1695
01:21:57,950 --> 01:22:01,450
physics has been driving at for some time.

1696
01:22:01,450 --> 01:22:06,450
The sort of continuous march of reductionism.

1697
01:22:06,450 --> 01:22:08,950
Smaller things made of smaller

1698
01:22:08,950 --> 01:22:11,450
things made of smaller things,

1699
01:22:11,450 --> 01:22:12,950
and some ultimate sense of

1700
01:22:12,950 --> 01:22:14,450
what the most fundamental thing is.

1701
01:22:14,450 --> 01:22:15,950
That does not seem to

1702
01:22:15,950 --> 01:22:17,450
be the way things are going.

1703
01:22:17,450 --> 01:22:20,450
The way things are going is,

1704
01:22:20,450 --> 01:22:22,450
that things morph into each other when

1705
01:22:22,450 --> 01:22:24,450
you change the parameters in the theory,

1706
01:22:24,450 --> 01:22:27,450
and what was fundamental can become composite,

1707
01:22:27,450 --> 01:22:29,450
what was composite can become fundamental.

1708
01:22:29,450 --> 01:22:34,450
What the ultimate lesson to learn there, nobody knows,

1709
01:22:34,450 --> 01:22:37,950
but it is a pattern that's

1710
01:22:37,950 --> 01:22:41,450
been emerging over the last 20 years,

1711
01:22:41,450 --> 01:22:44,450
both in quantum field theory,

1712
01:22:44,450 --> 01:22:49,450
that's here, electrons, and also in string theory.

1713
01:22:49,450 --> 01:22:52,450
So we'll hopefully get to see some of that.

1714
01:22:54,450 --> 01:22:56,450
We're finished, I think, with closed and open strings.

1715
01:22:56,450 --> 01:22:58,950
I think what we're going to

1716
01:22:58,950 --> 01:23:01,450
do is jump to a new subject,

1717
01:23:01,450 --> 01:23:03,450
which is string theory, of course,

1718
01:23:03,450 --> 01:23:06,450
but as seen from a totally different angle.

1719
01:23:06,450 --> 01:23:09,450
The angle that's called M-theory.

1720
01:23:09,450 --> 01:23:12,450
And I'm going to tell you what M-theory is,

1721
01:23:12,450 --> 01:23:15,450
and then how M-theory becomes string theory.

1722
01:23:15,450 --> 01:23:18,450
What we haven't talked about yet is why 26 dimensions,

1723
01:23:18,450 --> 01:23:20,450
why 10 dimensions.

1724
01:23:20,450 --> 01:23:21,950
We can talk about that,

1725
01:23:21,950 --> 01:23:23,450
but we can't talk about everything,

1726
01:23:23,450 --> 01:23:25,450
so I thought I would tell you what M-theory is,

1727
01:23:25,450 --> 01:23:28,450
and how it relates to string theory.

1728
01:23:28,450 --> 01:23:31,450
Okay, I think we're finished for tonight.

1729
